@Sam Lyons
Billie Holiday wore white gardenias in her hair and "little white flowers meant more to her than the lyric.  What came out of her when she sang "Gloomy Sunday" was real pain, not just borrowed morbidity.

I first heard it on my big sister's 78 rpm record player in 1945, when I was about 11 years old. I got it, even then.

@Dutchiris

Rezső Seress, the original songwriter and lyricist, had originally written this as a dirge for the post-WWI world. “The world has ended,” he sang. “Love has died.” So yes, the rewrite by a second-rate musical lyricist (Desmond Carter) is trite by comparison, especially on a day like today. 

This is not to take away from Billie Holliday’s cover or what the song meant to her. But Billie Holliday could take the most trite of lyrics and elevate them with her talent and heart. With or without her signature gardenias.

