@The X-Phile

Kasza is most often eaten with goulash (gulasz, for us), as it goes perfectly with saucy dishes. Roasted buckwheat groats (kasza gryczana prażona) is my favorite. A simple dish of kasza fried with onions and something fatty, like pork belly, is also popular. I've never seen kasza mixed with pasta. In fact, my wife considers it blasphemy to combine two starchy sides with any dish. It's either pasta or potatoes or kasza, but never more than 1 of those.

@Oikofuge

Except for kasza manna, we dont consider groats a breakfast dish, or a cereal, at all. Typically, kasza will be served as a starchy side to a main dish, like a roast, or goulash. Then it is cooked in water, drained dry, and on the plate you pour sauce or fat over it. I love me some kasza from time to time. It's dirt cheap, healthy(-ish, anyway), and goes well with many dishes.

Barley groats as a side dish are another Polish staple.

